      <article class="content">
        <p>I didn’t expect an <em>entry form</em> to make me cry. But there I was, typing out bios for my amigurumi, and something shifted. In describing my pieces, in naming who they were for and what they meant, I realized something I’d never said out loud: <strong>I am an artist.</strong></p>

        <p>Not just a crafter, not just someone “making things.” An artist.</p>

        <p>And now — these pieces are <strong>finalists</strong> in the <strong>Lands’ End Multicultural Art Showcase</strong>. They made it through round one. Which means someone else out there saw what I was too afraid to claim for myself: that these works are more than yarn. They’re story, spirit, healing.</p>

        <h2>Why Me, in a Multicultural Show?</h2>
        <p>I’ll admit it — the question crossed my mind and I even drafted a nice letter to the committee asking if I was even allowed to participate. <em>Why should a white woman from Wisconsin stand in a multicultural exhibition?</em></p>

        <p>The answer is <strong>amigurumi</strong> itself.</p>

        <p>Amigurumi is rooted in Japanese fiber arts, a tradition that believes handmade creations carry a spirit or “soul.” To gift one is to offer love, respect, and good fortune. When I crochet, I’m not just filling requests — I’m channeling that tradition and carrying it forward.</p>

        <p>Sometimes I make things for people who ask. But more often, something catches my eye and I think: <em>Oh my God, this is so <strong>[person’s name]</strong>.</em> Like when I saw a pattern and knew immediately it had to become a Pumpkin Amigurumi for my coworker <strong>Raija</strong>. Half Taylor Swift “Orange Era,” half unapologetically hot pink — it was just so <em>her</em>. That’s what amigurumi is for me: connection, recognition, celebration.</p>

        <h2>Healing in Stitches</h2>
        <p>Five years ago, <strong>The Woobles</strong> entered my life. And honestly? At first it was pure survival. We were on our annual road trip to the Florida panhandle — two in-laws, Porter, Blake, sometimes three dogs, all crammed in the truck. I needed something to do that didn’t involve screaming. Crochet became my outlet.</p>

        <p>Since then, amigurumi has been resilience, therapy, and sometimes straight-up sanity. I crocheted through liver disease. I crocheted in hospital rooms, hooking into the night while nurses checked my vitals. One of those finished pieces stayed with the nurses’ ward — a little reminder that healing goes both ways.</p>

        <p>Crochet has never been prayer for me. I’m an atheist. But it <em>is</em> meditation. It’s grounding. It’s rhythm and focus. It’s a reminder that even when my body was failing, my hands could still create.</p>

        <div class="hr"></div>

        <h2>The Works</h2>

        <h3>Aurora: Legacy & Light</h3>
        <p>Aurora is for my dearest friend of thirty years — mentor, guide, mother figure. She’s always seen my strength before I did, always lit the path. Puffins are her bird: resilient travelers who thrive in harsh landscapes. Aurora is both tribute and thank-you.</p>
        <figure class="inline">
          <img src="/img/Aurora.jpg" alt="Aurora the puffin amigurumi." />
          <figcaption>Aurora the puffin — stitched in gratitude for three decades of guidance and light.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Bonnie: Humor & Resilience</h3>
        <p>Bonnie has the wildest origin story of them all. She was supposed to be my “Trojan chicken.” The plan was dark and raw: crochet a chicken beautiful enough for my mother to proudly display, then fill it with slips of paper — my hurts, my rage, my childhood wounds. I was going to hand it to her, let her cut it open, and finally see all I’d carried. My counselor gently suggested there might be better ways to heal from childhood PTSD.</p>
        <p>So Bonnie transformed. She became something else, someone else’s. Instead of being a Trojan horse for pain, she became a tribute for a friend whose honesty, humor, and grounding presence has been a lifeline in my recovery. This “chicken lady” fills her home with warmth and resilience, and she’s far more worthy of such a gift than my mother ever was. Bonnie isn’t trauma anymore — she’s testimony.</p>
        <figure class="inline">
          <img src="/img/Bonnie.jpg" alt="Bonnie the chicken amigurumi." />
          <figcaption>Bonnie the chicken — once a Trojan plan, now a tribute to honest friendship.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Gilligan: Gratitude & Memories</h3>
        <p>Gilligan is a pelican for my mother-in-law, who became my family when my own mother couldn’t. He carries with him years of Florida beaches, dolphins, and seabird sightings — stitched memories of vacations and love. Gilligan isn’t just a bird; he’s a bond.</p>
        <figure class="inline">
          <img src="/img/Gilligan.jpg" alt="Gilligan the pelican amigurumi." />
          <figcaption>Gilligan the pelican — sun, salt, and family stitched into a companion.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Jade: Steadfast & Patience</h3>
        <p>Jade is a planter for my husband, whose love is steady even when my energy is chaos. He’s the soil to my swirl, the anchor that lets me grow wild. Succulents bloom in unlikely places — so does love, so does resilience. Jade is a reminder of that.</p>
        <figure class="inline">
          <img src="/img/Jade.jpg" alt="Jade succulent planter amigurumi." />
          <figcaption>Jade — a stitched planter for the anchor who lets me grow wild.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Bejeweled: Shimmer & Becoming</h3>
        <p>And then there’s Bejeweled. My peacock. My queen. My declaration. For years, I wore the mask of “everything is perfect” while I broke inside. Bejeweled is me, unmasked. She is feathers spread wide, shimmer unapologetic. She’s the reminder that the little girl inside me has finally arrived — radiant, worthy, seen.</p>
        <figure class="inline">
          <img src="/img/Bejeweled.jpg" alt="Bejeweled the peacock amigurumi." />
          <figcaption>Bejeweled — the moment of becoming, stitched in unapologetic shimmer.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="hr"></div>

        <h2>What This All Means</h2>
        <p>These pieces took time — hours I didn’t always have, deadlines I didn’t always plan well for. (Bonnie nearly didn’t make it, remember?) But they taught me patience, persistence, and the joy of finishing anyway.</p>
        <p>They taught me that art doesn’t have to hang in a gallery to matter. That being “an artist” isn’t about perfection, it’s about presence. And that sometimes, the truest art is the one that heals the person making it.</p>

        <section class="insight" role="note" aria-label="Pixie Insight">
          <div class="badge">Pixie<br/>Insight</div>
          <p style="margin:0;">Broken souls don’t need mending — they need making. Art doesn’t erase the cracks; it stitches them into story.</p>
        </section>

        <p class="mantra">
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span><strong>Mantra:</strong> I am an artist. My stitches are soulwork. My soul is worthy of light.</span>
        </p>

